Cyclistic - Market Insights Case Study

Aldrich Saladino

Overview and Introduction

Cyclistic is a bike-share company based in Chicago that looks to revolutionize city mobility with a diverse range of bicycles in service. Different bike tyoes, such as reclining bikes, hand tricycles and carge bikes are also available to accomodate customer needs. The variation of bicycles available and service has gotten them to expand and grow up to 5,824 bicycles since launching in 2016.

Purpose

This case study aims to dive into the usage of Cyclistics two primary user segments, casual riders and annual members. As a junior data analyst for Cyclistic on the Marketing team, we will identify and analyze trends on historical data surrounding trips on casual vs members. Understanding the distincions on usage is critical in planning and strategizing marketing campaigns that are effective. Using this data we can look to compare the differences between casual vs member, and the factors that determine why some users are casual and some are full members.

The goal is to find insights and data that can aid in the goal to converting casual members to full time members, and therefore increasing growth and market presence with increased profits.

Business Task

The primary objective in this analysis is to explore and identify differing bike usages and patterns among our casual and annual members. By examining aspects of usage such as frequency, duration and preferred bike types, recommendations the strategy on customer conversion and digital market growth can be made.

Data sources and preparation

The analysis uses historical bike trip data, spanning the previous 12 months from Cyclistic. The dataset, made by Motivate International Inc.provides comprehensive insights into the customer/user interactions along the bike-share system theyve created.

This dataset includes information regarding metrics such as trip durations, bike types used and docking stations.

Data Preparation Steps

  1. Data Acquisition The data is downloaded as a monthly CSV, and downloaded from Motivate International Inc.which holds Cylcistics bike trip data
  2. Data Organization Downloaded files are then organized and structured into a directory with separate subfolders. This is to delineate the raw and processed data upcoming
  3. Initial data Processing through spreadsheets Additional columns such as ride_length and day_of_week were created as a standard across all CSV files. The aim is to enhance the dataset to get more detail in the analysis.
  4. Data Cleaning Preliminary data cleaning involves seeking any values that are NA, or any missing values in columns within excel sheets. Further data cleaning is done within R to control what is being cleaned based on directed insight.

Data Processing and Cleaning

This will go over the steps and actions taken to further clean and process data, in preparation for analysis and insights. This includes steps to process to import and process the initial dataframe as a base for further analysis.

Tools and Approach

For processing and cleaning the Cyclistic bike-share data, Excel was used for a preliminary cleaning tool, due to its ease of use and simlicity while R was used for deeper cleaning due to its powerful manipulation capabilties and suitability for large dataset handling.

Cleaning in Excel

  1. Identify all missing values: This dataset had missing values within multiple various columns. This may be due in part to potential system errors in receiving usage history.
  • To maintain as much data as possible, missing values that did not have a negative impact on finding our solution were kept (start_station_name, end_station_name). Information such as invalid ride_lengths due to ended_at times being earlier then started_at has been ommited as a system error, with negative ride_length values.
  1. Formatting was done on new additional columns:
  • To ensure consistency once these are uploaded into R, columns have been checked over with the appropriate datatype and format

Cleaning and Processing R

Once the 12 excel CSV files have had an initial cleaning, further data manipulation/cleaning can be done within R. As mentioned R has powerful data manipulation capabilities, and is capable of handing large datasets like Cyclistics.

The first step is to place all cleaned CSVs into a subfolders as the directory. This allows us to upload the CSV path in preparation for ingesting all 12 months worth of data.

Confirm and prepare packages

Once we are ready to ingest and manipulate the data in R, the correct packages must be installed. The following packages are used in the cleaning and processing for analysis using the following code: * tidyverse * ggplot2 * dplyr * readr * janitor * skimr * scales

packages <- c("dplyr", "ggplot2", "tidyr", "readr", "tidyverse", "janitor", "skimr", "scales", "DT")

Cleaning Data

Within the historical data, there are some data with missing cells and line items. While unfortunate some data can still be used to aid in giving the most accurate insights possible and can be kept. In this situation there are 4 different types of insights we aim to gather to provide support to our problem: Usage Patterns, Popular Routes and Stations, Seasonality, Ride Lengths between the different demographics of members vs casual customers.

Any missing data under member_casual will need to be cleaned out, as it is not possible to determine which group the missing data belongs to. Furthermore day_of_week will be adjusted to mark down the exact day in words, rather than numbers for ease of understanding.

day_names <- c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday")

clean_df <- df_combined %>%
  filter(member_casual != "NA") %>%
  mutate(day_of_week = factor(day_names[day_of_week], levels = day_names)) %>%
  mutate(date_time_start = as.character(started_at)) %>%
  separate(date_time_start, into = c("start_date", "start_time"), sep = " ")

A final check once the cleaned dataframe has been made. This cleaned dataframe will serve as the base for other data manipulation endeavors.

Usage Patterns of Annual Members vs Casual Riders

A great way to start discerning the difference to annual members vs casual is to understand the initial usage, based on the average # of trips a day that each member type takes. ### Creating a Bar Chart for Trip frequency A new dataframe called total_trips was created as an intial starting point, and has been manipulated into daily_trips, which aims to include calculations of the average count per day.

# calculate trip count average per day
total_trips <- clean_df %>% 
  group_by(day_of_week, member_casual) %>% 
  summarize(total_trip_count = n())
daily_trips <- total_trips %>% 
  group_by(day_of_week, member_casual) %>% 
  summarize(average_trip_count = mean(total_trip_count))
# plotting bar chart
ggplot(daily_trips) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = day_of_week, y = average_trip_count, fill = member_casual), stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
labs(title = "Trip Frequency by Day of Week",
  x = "Day of Week",
  y = "Number of Trips",) +
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) + 
scale_y_continuous(labels = label_comma())

DT::datatable(daily_trips) #opens up a table to the data

The following insights were found: * Casual riders exhibit a significant increase in bike usage on weekends, indicating a recreational or non-commuter pattern of bike usage. * Members display a consistent usage pattern throughout the week, with slight increases on weekdays, suggesting a commuter or routine-based usage.

Popular Routes and Stations Data

Understanding the differences between members who are casual vs annual can be done through the pattern of destination. Annual members are likely to have common destinations, whilst casual members may have specified destinations that garner casual use. Here we look to confirm our assumptions.

Creating a chart on Station Frequency

A new dataframe is made specific to stations, so that custom aggregations for MoM (month over month) data can be explored.

#this will allow us to get start counts on a monthly basis per each Assuming 'clean_df' is your original data frame
station_df <- clean_df %>%
  filter(!is.na(start_station_name)) %>%
  mutate(
    # Replace "%m/%d/%Y" with the actual format of start_date in your data
    year_month = format(as.Date(start_date, format = "%m/%d/%Y"), "%Y-%m"),
    # Ensure start_time is in the correct format for conversion
    start_time = format(as.POSIXct(start_time, format = "%H:%M:%S"), "%H:%M:%S")
  )

station_df <- station_df %>% 
  select(ride_id,started_at,start_station_name,end_station_name,member_casual,ride_length,start_date,year_month,rideable_type)
#finding top 10 stations. Given the large list and various kinds
station_counts <- station_df %>%
  group_by(start_station_name, member_casual, year_month, rideable_type) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = "drop")

top_start_stations <- station_counts %>%
  group_by(member_casual, year_month) %>%
  slice_max(n = 5, order_by = count)
ggplot(top_start_stations) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = start_station_name, y = count), stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(title = "Top Stations by Frequency", 
    x = "Station Name", 
    y = "Number of Trips") +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual, scales = "free_x") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# View the data afterwards for supplementary information
DT::datatable(top_start_stations)

The following insights were found: * There is a concentration of trips among casual riders at specific stations, which are likely points of interest or recreational destinations. * Member trips are more evenly spread out across stations, aligning with the varied starting or ending points expected of regular commutes.

Determine bike preference based on member

bike_pref_df <- clean_df %>% 
  group_by(member_casual, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(total_bike_type_used = n(), .groups='drop') %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>% 
  mutate(percent_to_total = total_bike_type_used / sum(total_bike_type_used))

The following insights were found: * Electric bikes are preferred by a higher percentage of casual riders compared to members, possibly due to the ease of riding and novelty. * Members bike type usage is fairly balanced between classic and electric bikes, which could reflect a more practical approach to bike selection.

Recommendations based on analysis

Through the insights found through our analysis, and the patterns that are exhibited between casual vs annual members we can create a deeper understanding to the drivers of usage, reasons for member type, and potential options to create conversion to annual members.

Differences between Casual Riders and Annual Members

  • Annual Members: They use the bikes more consistently throughout the week, suggesting that the bikes are part of their regular routine, likely for commuting to work or school. Their trip lengths are relatively stable, indicating a pattern of regular, predictable use.
  • Casual Riders: They predominantly use bikes on weekends and for longer periods, especially in warmer months, which implies recreational use or as a transportation method during leisure activities. Their preference for electric bikes and the concentration of trips at specific stations suggest they use the service for occasional exploration or tourism.

Reasons Casual Riders may look to buy Cyclistic Annual Memberships

  • Cost Savings: Casual riders who use the service frequently enough may find that an annual membership is more cost-effective than paying per ride.
  • Convenience: Membership could offer additional benefits such as expedited bike checkout, which could be appealing for frequent use.
  • Commitment to Health and Environment: Riders may be motivated to switch to a more sustainable mode of transportation that also offers health benefits, aligning with personal or social values.
  • Incentives and Promotions: Targeted promotions for casual riders, such as discounted trial memberships or exclusive member benefits, could entice them to try out and ultimately commit to an annual membership.

Potential implementations using Digital Media to Spur Casual Rider conversion

  • Targeted Advertising: Use data insights to create targeted ad campaigns for casual riders on platforms they frequent. Highlight the benefits of membership, especially during peak usage times like weekends and summer months.
  • Engagement Campaigns: Run social media campaigns that engage casual riders with challenges, incentives, and shareable content to create a sense of community they might want to join.
  • Content Marketing: Develop content that showcases the benefits of switching to annual membership, including member testimonials, cost comparison calculators, and the environmental impact of cycling versus driving.
  • Email Marketing: Implement an email nurture campaign that provides casual riders with personalized content and special offers to encourage membership sign-up.
  • Analytics-Driven Insights: Utilize user engagement and conversion data to continually refine digital strategies, ensuring the marketing efforts are effective and efficient.

Conclusion

The analysis of Cyclistics data has depicted clear distincions in usage patterns between annual members and its casual members. Annual members consistently utilize the ride-share service for daily commute and transportation. In contrast casual riders primarily use the service during weekends and warmer months, with longer trips during this time, suggesting recreational, explorational or tourism reasons.

As a potential opportunity to convert, the casual rider demographic bolsters a multifacted approach to the percieved opportunity. Economic, convenience and environmental incentives take to the forefront as some reasons that casual riders can be motivated by. To appease to these opportunities, the use of digital media and marketing, and how its leveraged will be key to influencing these users

To capitalize on these insights, Cyclistic is recommended to implement targeted digital marketing campaigns that align with casual riders habits, harness the power of engaging content to communicate the value of memberships, and utilize analytical tools to refine marketing approaches continually. By focusing on the convenience, cost savings, and additional benefits that come with membership, along with a robust digital presence that resonates with casual riders values and preferences, Cyclistic can create a compelling proposition for converting casual riders to loyal members.

In summary, the path forward for Cyclistic involves a combination of strategic promotions, value-driven communication, and enhanced digital engagement, all informed by the rich data insights at their disposal. Through concerted efforts in these areas, Cyclistic can expect to see a stronger community of annual members, thereby driving growth and fostering a more sustainable, health-conscious mode of transportation within the community
